cs.CV, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.RO, cs.NE 

This paper is primarily focused on visual reasoning and understanding of physics, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes an evaluation framework and benchmark dataset for testing and improving artificial systems' understanding of physics, which falls under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of deep neural networks for future frame prediction and analysis of their results also suggests that the paper may belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The proposed framework and benchmark dataset can also be used for robotics applications, which suggests that the paper may belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Finally, the use of neural networks for unsupervised learning and analysis of their limitations suggests that the paper may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
